Ashborn communities maintain the Ember Crucible's heat-trial as a living practice, not merely a historical certification reference.
For Ashborn, the Crucible trial tests whether a person has the correct relationship with intense heat, not merely whether they can survive it.
The correct relationship is forge-discipline: heat commands respect, not fear; it is used, not merely endured.
Ashborn Crucible witnesses assess quality of judgment under heat — a caravan that loses animals but preserves cargo through correct triage shows better forge-discipline than one that preserves animals at cargo cost.
Ashborn communities maintain separate granular records of Crucible assessment outcomes, available to caravan operators seeking Ashborn-community trade partnerships.
